## bead-substrate-missing

Date: 2026-05-09

Promotion Action: NEW (sibling-of bead-missing-from-local-db)

Class: `bead-substrate-missing`

Event Count: 7 events in 7 days

Severity: medium (1 medium + 5 medium + 1 low; aggregated medium
because force-close after `ISSUE_NOT_FOUND` is medium-severity
substrate divergence)

Cost: Seven worker dispatches received `br show / br close`
`ISSUE_NOT_FOUND` against bead IDs (`josh-q32zp`, `josh-8lliy`,
`josh-8kp1u`, `josh-c8tqy`, `josh-e84oj`, `josh-qrp79`, `josh-ylpa3`)
that the dispatch packet referenced. Each worker proceeded with
force-close or narrow-scope work despite no local bead row. The
dispatched bead IDs use the `josh-*` prefix namespace which is
distinct from the `flywheel-*` / `bd-*` defaults; this points at a
cross-repo bead-id leak or a frankensqlite bead-DB row gap.

Root Cause: Cosmetic class-name variant of
`bead-missing-from-local-db`. Both classes describe the same trauma:
a dispatched bead is not present in the local `br` substrate. The
two class names emerged from slightly different fuckup-log writers
(the `--class` argument string differs across worker preflights).
Doctrine ladder treated them as distinct, filing both
`flywheel-s2yd8` (3 events) and `flywheel-uyd9i` (7 events) as
independent promotion candidates.

Forever-Rule: A `br show / br close ISSUE_NOT_FOUND` against a
dispatched bead is a substrate divergence, not permission to silently
force-close. The worker must (a) record the missing-bead event with
exact bead-id and substrate path, (b) check for cross-repo bead-id
leaks (per `flywheel-2xdi.30`-class doctrine on bead-isolation), and
(c) only force-close after the dispatch's source orchestrator
confirms the bead-id is canonical. Future fuckup-log writers should
use the canonical class name `bead-missing-from-local-db`; the
`bead-substrate-missing` alias remains for backwards-compat in
historical fuckup-log rows.

Fix Applied/Status: NEW layer-2 INCIDENTS entry from
`/flywheel:learn --promote bead-substrate-missing` (worker-tick by
`flywheel-uyd9i`). Sibling-class to `bead-missing-from-local-db`
(authored by `flywheel-s2yd8`); future fuckup-log writers are
encouraged to use the canonical sibling class. This entry exists so
historical `bead-substrate-missing` rows have an INCIDENTS landing
pad and the doctrine-ladder dedup heuristic
(`doctrine-ladder-promote.sh`, fixed by `flywheel-qnkj2` to search
repo-local INCIDENTS.md) sees the section.

